---
import SiteLayout from "../../../layouts/SiteLayout.astro";
const schema = [
  {
    "@context": "https://schema.org",
    "@type": "Article",
    "headline": "What is Your FI Number? Calculator and the 25x Rule",
    "description": "Calculate your Financial Independence (FI) number using the 25x rule. Learn how to adjust for inflation, pensions, and social security.",
    "author": {
      "@type": "Organization",
      "name": "Fire Maths"
    }
  },
  {
    "@context": "https://schema.org",
    "@type": "FAQPage",
    "mainEntity": [
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "Why do I multiply by 25?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Multiplying by 25 is the mathematical inverse of the 4% rule (100 / 4 = 25). If you need to withdraw 4% of your portfolio to live, your portfolio must be 25 times your annual expenses."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "Should my FI number be based on my current income or current expenses?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Your FI number should be based entirely on your projected FUTURE expenses in retirement, not your current income or current expenses. When you retire, you will no longer be saving for retirement or paying payroll taxes, which often drastically reduces your necessary income."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "Does the FI number include my house?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Usually, no. Your FI number represents the invested, income-producing assets (stocks, bonds, rental properties) needed to generate cash flow. Your primary residence does not generate cash flow, so it is generally excluded from your FI portfolio, though a paid-off house dramatically lowers your required annual expenses."
        }
      }
    ]
  }
];
---
<SiteLayout site="firemaths" title="What is Your FI Number? Calculate Your FIRE Target" description="Use our interactive FI Number calculator to find out exactly how much you need to invest to achieve Financial Independence." canonical="https://firemaths.info/what-is-fi-number" schema={schema}>
  <div class="page-content">
    <div class="hero">
      <h1>Calculate Your FI Number</h1>
      <p>Find your finish line. Exactly how much do you need to retire early?</p>
    </div>

    <div class="card calc-card">
      <h3 style="margin-top:0">Interactive FI Number Calculator</h3>
      <div class="input-group">
        <label>Expected Annual Retirement Expenses ($)</label>
        <input type="number" id="annualExpenses" value="60000" />
      </div>
      <div class="input-group">
        <label>Guaranteed Annual Income (Pension, Real Estate, etc.) ($)</label>
        <input type="number" id="otherIncome" value="0" />
      </div>
      <div class="input-group">
        <label>Safe Withdrawal Rate (%)</label>
        <input type="number" id="swr" value="4.0" step="0.1" />
      </div>
      <button onclick="calculateFiNumber()">Calculate My FI Number</button>

      <div class="results" id="calcResults" style="display:none;">
        <div class="result-row">
          <span>Portfolio Income Needed:</span>
          <span id="portfolioIncome" class="value"></span>
        </div>
        <div class="result-row">
          <span>Target Multiple:</span>
          <span id="targetMultiple" class="value"></span>
        </div>
        <div class="result-row total">
          <span>Your FI Number:</span>
          <span id="fiNumber" class="value highlight"></span>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="article-content">

      <h2>The Milestone: Your Financial Independence Number</h2>
      <p>If you are pursuing Financial Independence and Early Retirement (FIRE), you need a finish line. You need a concrete, mathematical target that, once crossed, means work is officially optional. That target is your <strong>FI Number</strong>.</p>

      <p>Your FI Number is the total value of invested assets you need to accumulate to cover all your living expenses for the rest of your life without ever needing to work again.</p>

      <h3>The 25x Rule (The Math Behind the Number)</h3>
      <p>The standard way to calculate your FI number is incredibly simple: <strong>Multiply your expected annual retirement expenses by 25.</strong></p>

      <p>This "25x Rule" is derived directly from the <a href="/safe-withdrawal-rate-explained">Safe Withdrawal Rate</a> (specifically, the 4% rule established by the Trinity Study). Mathematically, withdrawing 4% of a portfolio is the exact same thing as dividing that portfolio by 25. Therefore, to figure out how big the portfolio needs to be to support a specific withdrawal amount, you multiply that amount by 25.</p>

      <h4>Examples of FI Numbers</h4>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Lean FIRE ($40k/yr spend):</strong> $40,000 x 25 = <strong>$1,000,000</strong></li>
        <li><strong>Chubby FIRE ($80k/yr spend):</strong> $80,000 x 25 = <strong>$2,000,000</strong></li>
        <li><strong>Fat FIRE ($150k/yr spend):</strong> $150,000 x 25 = <strong>$3,750,000</strong></li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Step 1: Determine Your Future Expenses</h3>
      <p>The biggest mistake beginners make is calculating their FI number based on their <em>current gross income</em>. Your FI number has nothing to do with what you earn; it is entirely dependent on what you will <strong>spend</strong> in retirement.</p>

      <p>Your retirement budget will look very different from your working budget. Here is why your expenses will likely drop:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>No more saving:</strong> You are currently saving 20% to 50% of your income for retirement. In retirement, that expense vanishes.</li>
        <li><strong>Lower taxes:</strong> You will no longer pay FICA/payroll taxes. Your income will likely be lower, and capital gains are taxed at a much lower rate than W-2 income.</li>
        <li><strong>Paid-off mortgage:</strong> Many retirees aim to have their mortgage paid off by the time they hit FI, erasing their largest monthly bill.</li>
        <li><strong>Work-related expenses:</strong> Commuting, professional wardrobes, and buying lunch at the office all disappear.</li>
      </ul>
      <p>However, some expenses will increase, most notably <strong>healthcare</strong> (especially if you retire before Medicare kicks in) and travel/entertainment.</p>

      <h3>Step 2: Adjusting for Other Income Streams</h3>
      <p>The 25x rule assumes your investment portfolio has to carry 100% of the weight of your retirement. But what if you have other income streams? You can subtract guaranteed future income from your annual expense number before multiplying by 25.</p>

      <p><strong>Example: Accounting for Social Security or a Pension</strong></p>
      <p>Let's say you expect to spend $60,000 a year in retirement. Under the standard rule, your FI number is $1.5 million ($60,000 x 25).</p>
      <p>However, you know you will receive $20,000 a year from a government pension.</p>
      <ul>
        <li>Total Expenses: $60,000</li>
        <li>Minus Pension Income: -$20,000</li>
        <li><strong>Portfolio Dependency: $40,000</strong></li>
      </ul>
      <p>You only need your portfolio to generate $40,000 a year. Therefore, your actual FI number is $1,000,000 ($40,000 x 25). The pension just saved you from having to accumulate a half-million dollars!</p>

      <p>The same math applies if you plan to do <a href="/what-is-barista-fire">Barista FIRE</a> (part-time work) or if you own cash-flowing rental properties.</p>

      <h3>Should You Use 30x Instead of 25x?</h3>
      <p>The 4% rule (25x) was based on a 30-year retirement. If you plan to retire at 35, your money needs to last 50 or 60 years. To protect against <a href="/sequence-of-returns-risk">Sequence of Returns Risk</a>, many early retirees use a more conservative Safe Withdrawal Rate of 3.3% to 3.5%.</p>

      <ul>
        <li><strong>3.33% SWR:</strong> Multiply expenses by <strong>30</strong>.</li>
        <li><strong>3.00% SWR:</strong> Multiply expenses by <strong>33.3</strong>.</li>
      </ul>
      <p>Using a 30x multiple provides a massive margin of safety, but it will also add years to your working life.</p>

      <p>For more terms and concepts, visit our <a href="/fire-dictionary">Complete FIRE Dictionary</a>.</p>

    </div>

    <div class="faq-section">
      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
      <div class="card faq-card">
        <h3>Why do I multiply by 25?</h3>
        <p>Multiplying by 25 is the mathematical inverse of the 4% rule (100 / 4 = 25). If you need to withdraw 4% of your portfolio to live, your portfolio must be 25 times your annual expenses.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="card faq-card">
        <h3>Should my FI number be based on my current income or current expenses?</h3>
        <p>Your FI number should be based entirely on your projected FUTURE expenses in retirement, not your current income or current expenses. When you retire, you will no longer be saving for retirement or paying payroll taxes, which often drastically reduces your necessary income.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="card faq-card">
        <h3>Does the FI number include my house?</h3>
        <p>Usually, no. Your FI number represents the invested, income-producing assets (stocks, bonds, rental properties) needed to generate cash flow. Your primary residence does not generate cash flow, so it is generally excluded from your FI portfolio, though a paid-off house dramatically lowers your required annual expenses.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
  <script is:inline>
    function calculateFiNumber() {
      const annualExpenses = parseFloat(document.getElementById('annualExpenses').value);
      const otherIncome = parseFloat(document.getElementById('otherIncome').value) || 0;
      const swr = parseFloat(document.getElementById('swr').value);

      if (isNaN(annualExpenses) || isNaN(swr) || swr <= 0) return;

      const portfolioIncomeNeeded = Math.max(0, annualExpenses - otherIncome);
      const multiple = 100 / swr;
      const fiNumber = portfolioIncomeNeeded * multiple;

      const formatter = new Intl.NumberFormat('en-US', { style: 'currency', currency: 'USD', maximumFractionDigits: 0 });

      document.getElementById('portfolioIncome').innerText = formatter.format(portfolioIncomeNeeded) + " / yr";
      document.getElementById('targetMultiple').innerText = multiple.toFixed(1) + "x";
      document.getElementById('fiNumber').innerText = formatter.format(fiNumber);

      document.getElementById('calcResults').style.display = 'block';
    }
  </script>
  <style is:inline>
    .page-content { max-width: 900px; margin: 0 auto; padding: 2rem 1.5rem; }
    .hero { text-align: center; padding: 3rem 0 2rem; }
    .hero h1 { font-size: 2.2rem; font-weight: 800; margin-bottom: 0.5rem; }
    .hero p { color: var(--text-secondary); font-size: 1.1rem; max-width: 600px; margin: 0 auto; line-height: 1.6; }
    .card { background: var(--card-bg); border: 1px solid var(--border-color); border-radius: 12px; padding: 1.5rem; margin: 1.5rem 0; }

    .calc-card { background: color-mix(in srgb, var(--card-bg) 80%, var(--accent-color) 5%); border-color: color-mix(in srgb, var(--border-color) 50%, var(--accent-color) 30%); }
    .input-group { margin-bottom: 1rem; display: flex; flex-direction: column; }
    .input-group label { margin-bottom: 0.5rem; color: var(--text-secondary); font-size: 0.9rem; font-weight: 600; text-transform: uppercase; letter-spacing: 0.5px; }
    .input-group input { background: var(--bg-color); border: 1px solid var(--border-color); color: var(--text-primary); padding: 0.75rem; border-radius: 6px; font-family: 'JetBrains Mono', monospace; font-size: 1rem; width: 100%; box-sizing: border-box; }
    .input-group input:focus { outline: none; border-color: var(--accent-color); }
    button { background: var(--accent-color); color: #000; border: none; padding: 1rem; border-radius: 6px; font-size: 1rem; font-weight: 700; cursor: pointer; width: 100%; margin-top: 1rem; transition: opacity 0.2s; }
    button:hover { opacity: 0.9; }

    .results { margin-top: 2rem; padding-top: 1.5rem; border-top: 1px dashed var(--border-color); }
    .result-row { display: flex; justify-content: space-between; margin-bottom: 1rem; font-size: 1.1rem; }
    .result-row.total { font-size: 1.4rem; font-weight: 700; margin-top: 1rem; padding-top: 1rem; border-top: 1px solid var(--border-color); }
    .value { font-family: 'JetBrains Mono', monospace; }
    .highlight { color: var(--accent-color); }

    .article-content { margin-top: 3rem; line-height: 1.7; color: var(--text-primary); }
    .article-content h2 { font-size: 1.8rem; margin: 2rem 0 1rem; color: #fff; }
    .article-content h3 { font-size: 1.4rem; margin: 1.5rem 0 1rem; color: var(--accent-color); }
    .article-content h4 { font-size: 1.2rem; margin: 1.2rem 0 0.8rem; color: #e0e0e0; }
    .article-content p { margin-bottom: 1.2rem; }
    .article-content ul, .article-content ol { margin-bottom: 1.5rem; padding-left: 1.5rem; }
    .article-content li { margin-bottom: 0.5rem; }
    .article-content a { color: var(--accent-color); text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 1px dotted var(--accent-color); }
    .article-content a:hover { border-bottom-style: solid; }

    .faq-section { margin-top: 4rem; border-top: 2px solid var(--border-color); padding-top: 2rem; }
    .faq-section h2 { text-align: center; margin-bottom: 2rem; font-size: 2rem; }
    .faq-card h3 { font-size: 1.2rem; margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: var(--text-primary); }
    .faq-card p { color: var(--text-secondary); line-height: 1.6; margin: 0; }
  </style>
</SiteLayout>
